The paper deals with trellises, which are commonly used in coding theory and information theory. The abstract mentions the product construction of Kschischang and Sorokine, which is a well-known technique in coding theory. The paper also introduces new properties of characteristic matrices, which are used in the construction of tail-biting trellises. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.IT (Information Theory). The paper also deals with matrices and their properties, which suggests that it could belong to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) or cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). The paper also mentions duality and lexicographical ordering, which are topics in cs.CC (Computational Complexity) and cs.LG (Machine Learning).
